Here's a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing html formatted text using the [CommonMark library](https://github.com/commonmark/commonmark-cpp) for parsing the markdown:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <commonmark/commonmark.h>

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
    try {
        // Parse the markdown into an AST (Abstract Syntax Tree)
        commonmark::Parser parser;
        auto ast = parser.parse(markdown);

        // Convert the AST to HTML using the CommonMark library's visitor
        std::ostringstream html_ss;
        commonmark::HtmlVisitor html_visitor;
        html_visitor.visit(ast);
        std::string html = html_ss.str();

        return html;
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        std::cerr << "Error: " << e.what() << "\n";
        return "";
    }
}
```

The function uses the CommonMark library to parse the markdown into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) and then converts the AST to HTML using the `commonmark::HtmlVisitor`. If there's an error during parsing, it will print the error message and return an empty string.

